stanford digital repository stanford digital repository learning via prediction mapping continuous stimuli to discrete symbols creator november adam daniel contributor s ramscar michael primary advisor thomas ewart ac primary advisor mcclelland james l advisor stanford university dept of psychology description how do we use and represent words how do we learn to break up the dimensions of continuous variation of the world into discrete categories in this thesis i explore how recasting this problem in terms of simple prediction provides insight into the computational nature of word learning through a series of computational simulations and human experiments that manipulate the structure of information in time i find that when using features of the world to predict words the representations learned are likely to be more useful for discriminating the appropriate response however these representations are also likely to be distorted favoring diagnostic information and thus sacrificing general utility across contexts at the same time trying to use words to predict the relevant features of the world will result in less distorted representations but will not enhance discrimination demonstrating these effects while controlling for various potentially confounding variables strengthens the case that prediction is central to word learning adam daniel november submitted to the department of psychology thesis ph d stanford university 2010 view in searchworks 2010 by adam daniel november this work is licensed under a creative commons attribution noncommercial 3.0 unported license file download description access november augmented pdf body of dissertation stanford only until 2012 08 27 stanford university stanford california 94305 650 725 1064 terms of use copyright complaints
